module.exports = {"artists":[{"name":"Couple Two T'ree","info":"How  would  you  describe  your  show? \n\n We're  both  pretty  deep  in  soul  and  funk  45s  so  that  tends  to  make  up  the  majority  of  our  shows,  but  we  also  collect  other  genres:  Latin,  Jamaican,  garage  rock,  psych,  city  pop,  etc.  We  both  have  a  similar  sensibility  towards  record  collecting  in  terms  of  what  we  listen  for,  the  focus  being  on  obscure  sounds. \n If  you’re  in  a  collective,  how  did  you  meet  each  other? \n I  (Joe)  have  been  playing  in  punk  and  hardcore  bands  since  I  was  14,  and  I'vebeen  collecting  records  for  just  as  long.  My  taste  grew  as  a  record  collector/enthusiast  out  a  desire  to  be  a  better,  well  informed  musician.  I  still  play  in  a  hardcore  band,  The  Lion's  Cage,  and  even  though  the  music  I  createis  pretty  different  than  what  I  buy,  collect  and  DJ  the  two  play  a  large  role  in  informing  each  other. \n If  you  have  guests,  how  do  you  find  and  determine  guests  for  your  show?  There's  a  decent  amount  of  45  collectors  living  in  NY,  people  I've  been  good  friends  over  the  years  through  the  45  scene.  I  often  ask  those  friend's  to  fill  in  on  the  show,  people  I  know  who  have  a  similar  style  to  Couple  Two  T'ree.  Each  of  those  collectors  has  a  slightly  different  sound  in  what  they  look  for  in  45s,  if  you  listen  carefully  to  can  start  to  pick  out  a  DJ's  \"sound.\"  Often  we  end  up  attributing  45s  to  that  DJ,  like  \"Oh,  this  sounds  like  a  Joe  45\"  because  it  fits  pretty  well  into  my  individual  sensibility.  This  leaves  room  for  guests  to  come  on  the  show  that  fit  the  format  but  also  bring  something  new  and  interesting  to  the  table. \n How  does  the  Lot  feel  different  than  other  radio  stations? \n The  Lot  is  different  in  so  many  ways  but  primarily  I'd  say  the  diversity  of  DJs  and  the  emphasis  on  passion.  We  were  one  of  the  earliest  regular  shows  on  the  station  and  I  remember  Francois  giving  us  some  praise  for  our  apparent  passion  for  what  we  do.  That  always  stuck  with  me  and  I've  realized  that's  magic  potion  for  what  has  made  The  Lot  so  amazing.  Every  single  DJ,  guest  or  regular,  that  blesses  that  shipping  container  is  abundantly  passionate  about  music.  That's  what  brought  Alston  and  I  together  as  friends,  our  mutual  passion  for  collecting  45s  and  DJing  and  that's  what  drives  us  to  do  this.show \n In  what  ways  has  your  involvement  with  the  Lot  changed  how  you  think  about  music  today? \n The  Lot  has  facilitated  a  super  solid  community  of  DJs  and  collectors  and  through  that  I've  met  some  incredible  people.  That  sense  of  community  has  made  me  even  more  stoked  to  be  doing  the  show  and  sharing  my  collection.  On  the  flip  The  Lot  has  also  opened  my  mind  to  some  new  stuff  that  I  was  never  into,  house  music  specifically.  Recently  started  going  down  that  hole  and  that's  something  I  would  have  never  saw  myself  getting  into  a  few  years  ago. \n Are  you  connected  with  your  listeners?  If  so,  how? \n Every  Sunday  there's  the  same  handful  of  listeners  active  in  the  chatroom,  shout  out  Biker  Bob,  Jorg,  Dud,  Toast,  NIC!  It's  pretty  incredible  to  have  real  time  interaction  with  listeners,  to  share  information  about  the  records  and  just  shoot  the  shit.  It's  actually  one  of  my  favorite  things  about  doing  the  show. \n How  has  the  art  of  DJing  changed  with  the  rise  of  streaming  services? \n For  me  personally  the  cameras  were  the  big  variable  in  terms  of  live  stream  DJing.  For  a  few  reasons.  I've  never  really  considered  myself  a  DJ,  I'm  not  very  good  from  a  technical  perspective,  but  since  the  inception  of  CTT  I've  made  a  point  to  get  better.  Knowing  that  people  are  listening  and  watching  itcan  be  kind  of  embarrassing  if  you  mess  up.  Second,  there's  a  little  bit  of  a  pressure  to  put  on  a  performance.  It's  not  always  the  most  interesting  to  just  watch  two  dudes  fuck  around  and  nerd  out  with  some  45s  on  a  live  stream,  but  if  those  two  dudes  are  clapping  and  dancing  and  genuinely  having  a  good  time  it's  a  different  story.  Alston  and  I  are  both  super  animate  when  we  DJ  out,  and  the  same  goes  for  when  were  on  air.  I  want  people  to  see  us  on  the  live  stream  and  go  \"those  fucking  dudes  love  what  their  doing.\" \n How  do  you  see  The  Lot  evolving? \n It's  hard  to  picture  where  The  Lot  will  be  in  a  year,  or  two,  or  three.  When  it  first  started  it  was  pretty  bare  bones  and  reflecting  on  how  far  it  has  come  in  the  past  two  years  its  unbelievable.  We  recently  had  our  two  year  anniversary  party  at  Brooklyn  Bazaar.  That  night  was  the  most  transformative  night  I've  ever  had  as  a  DJ,  a  collector,  a  musician,  and  a  music  lover.  There  were  so  many  people  are  that  party  that  you  could  barely  walk  from  room  to  room  the  whole  night.  It's  a  difficult  feeling  to  describeIt's  hard  to  picture  where  The  Lot  will  be  in  a  year,  or  two,  or  three.  When  it  first  started  it  was  pretty  bare  bones  and  reflecting  on  how  far  it  has  come  in  the  past  two  years  its  unbelievable.  We  recently  had  our  two  year  anniversary  party  at  Brooklyn  Bazaar.  That  night  was  the  most  transformative  night  I've  ever  had  as  a  DJ,  a  collector,  a  musician,  and  a  music  lover.  There  were  so  many  people  are  that  party  that  you  could  barely  walk  from  room  to  room  the  whole  night.  It's  a  difficult  feeling  to  describe but that  set  we  DJed  at  the  party  was  the  most  important  thing  I've  ever  done  as  a  DJ,  I  felt  legitimately  part  of  something  beautiful  and  important  in  a  way  I  have  never  before.  It  was  a  truly  affirming  and  positive  experience.  So  after  that  it's  hard  to  picture  where  the  station  will  go  in  the  next  few  years,  but  Francois  is  a  genius  and  all  the  people  involved  in  making  The  Lot  happen  are  so  driven  and  passionate  to  spread  the  message.  Wherever  it's  going  from  here  is  going  to  be  tremendous. ","stage_name":"Couple Two T’ree","real_name":"Joe Cristando & Alston Paresa","hometown":"Long Island & Hawaii","years":"Joe, 8;Alston, 19.","mixcloud":"https://www.mixcloud.com/thelotradio/playlists/couple-two-tree","image_one":"/images/Alston&Joe_01.jpg","image_two":"/images/Alston&Joe_02.jpg","image_three":"/images/Alston&Joe_03.jpg"},{"name":"Camille Vourzay","info":"How would you describe your show? \n It’s the reflection of what inspires me. Travels, people. Mostly funk music, disco, soul and rock n roll. \n What’s your relationship with music? (i.e. musician, enthusiast, work in the industry, etc.) In general, how does your daily life inform your show? \n I run a record label called Beef Wellington records and I work at a record shop in the city and I book shows. My daily life informs my show as soon as I arrive at work! \n Name: Camille VourzayShow Name: Camille BWRHometown: Clermont­Ferrand, France; Paris, France. Years of DJing: 5 yearsHow would you describe your show? It’s the reflection of what inspires me. Travels, people. Mostly funk music, disco, soul and rock n roll.What’s your relationship with music? (i.e. musician, enthusiast, work in the industry, etc.) In general, how does your daily life inform your show? I run a record label called Beef Wellington records and I work at a record shop in the city and I book shows. My daily life informs my show as soon as I arrive at work!If you have guests, how do you find and determine guests for your show? \n Most of the time they are friends and/or coworkers or DJs that I met at their gig and I invited them. \n Name: Camille VourzayShow Name: Camille BWRHometown: Clermont­Ferrand, France; Paris, France. Years of DJing: 5 yearsHow would you describe your show? It’s the reflection of what inspires me. Travels, people. Mostly funk music, disco, soul and rock n roll.What’s your relationship with music? (i.e. musician, enthusiast, work in the industry, etc.) In general, how does your daily life inform your show? I run a record label called Beef Wellington records and I work at a record shop in the city and I book shows. My daily life informs my show as soon as I arrive at work!If you have guests, how do you find and determine guests for your show?Most of the time they are friends and/or coworkers or DJs that I met at their gig and I invited them.How does The Lot feel different than other radio stations? \n It’s different because it mixes a really large spectrum of people but you still feel it’s the same big family in a way. \n In what ways has your involvement with The Lot changed how you think about music today? \n It didn’t change my involvement, but it pushes me to have new records almost each time and be better (at least trying to!) \n Are you connected with your listeners? If so, how? \n A bit yes, by the different social networks and sometimes I meet them during a set. \n How has the art of DJing changed with the rise of streaming services? \n It’s the contradiction spirit. The more the streaming services rise, the more I’m gonna tryto find some tunes that they are not on those streaming services!","show_name":"Camille BWR","real_name":"Camille Vourzay","years":"5 years","hometown":"Clermont­Ferrand, France; Paris, France.","mixcloud":"https://www.mixcloud.com/thelotradio/camille-the-lot-radio-12082017/","image_one":"/images/Camille_Vourzay_01.jpg","image_two":"/images/Camille_Vourzay_02.jpg","image_three":"/images/Camille_Vourzay_03.jpg"},{"name":"Charlotte von Kotze","info":"Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry's standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum. Lorem Ipsum is simply dummy text of the printing and typesetting industry. Lorem Ipsum has been the industry's standard dummy text ever since the 1500s, when an unknown printer took a galley of type and scrambled it to make a type specimen book. It has survived not only five centuries, but also the leap into electronic typesetting, remaining essentially unchanged. It was popularised in the 1960s with the release of Letraset sheets containing Lorem Ipsum passages, and more recently with desktop publishing software like Aldus PageMaker including versions of Lorem Ipsum.","show_name":"Brøøklyn English","real_name":"Charlotte von Kotze","years":" I have actively been collecting music for the last 8 years. I have been curating music for videos (Music Supervision) for the last 4­5 years and I have been DJing / playing music publicly at The Lot and here and there at some locations in the neighborhood for the last year (Achilles’ Heel, Donna Brooklyn, Project Parlor...etc.) However, I am not a regular professional DJ playing at clubs on the day­to­day.","hometown":"Brooklyn; Paris, France; Berlin, Germany","mixcloud":"https://www.mixcloud.com/thelotradio/camille-the-lot-radio-12082017/","image_one":"/images/Charlotte_Von_Kotz